<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-what-is-de" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>What is a Differential Equation?</title>

  <p><em>Modelling situations that are changing</em></p>

  <p>
    Derivatives are used to model changing situations. Things are changing all around us.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Guided Question.</strong>
    Come up with an equation that models the following situation:
    The rate of change of a population P(t) is proportional to the current population.
  </p>

  <!-- DEFINITION -->
  <definition xml:id="def-de">
    <title>Differential Equation</title>

    <p>
      A differential equation is an equation involving a function, its derivatives, and the independent variable.
    </p>

    <p>
      The order of a differential equation is the highest derivative appearing.
    </p>
  </definition>

  <!-- EXAMPLE 1 -->
  <exercise xml:id="ex-pop-model">
    

    <p>
      A simple model assumes:
    </p>

    <p><me>dP/dt = kP</me></p>

    <p><strong>Find the general solution.</strong></p>

    <solution>

      <p><strong>Step 1: Separate variables</strong></p>
      <hint>
        <p>Divide both sides by P to isolate variables.</p>
      </hint>

      <p><me>dP/P = k dt</me></p>

      <p><strong>Step 2: Integrate both sides</strong></p>
      <hint>
        <p>Use that ∫1/P dP = ln|P|.</p>
      </hint>

      <p><me>\ln|P| = kt + C</me></p>

      <p><strong>Step 3: Solve for P</strong></p>
      <hint>
        <p>Exponentiate both sides and absorb constants.</p>
      </hint>

      <p><me>P(t) = Ce^{kt}</me></p>

    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <!-- EXAMPLE 2 -->
  <example xml:id="ex-ivp">
    <title>Initial Conditions</title>

    <p>
      Solve:
    </p>

    <p><me>dP/dt = 2P, \quad P(0)=200</me></p>

    <solution>

      <p><strong>Step 1: Solve differential equation</strong></p>
      <hint>
        <p>This is the same form as exponential growth.</p>
      </hint>

      <p><me>P(t) = Ce^{2t}</me></p>

      <p><strong>Step 2: Apply initial condition</strong></p>
      <hint>
        <p>Substitute t = 0 and P(0) = 200.</p>
      </hint>

      <p><me>200 = C</me></p>

      <p><strong>Final answer</strong></p>
      <p><me>P(t) = 200e^{2t}</me></p>

    </solution>
  </example>

  <!-- SETUP MODELS -->
  <example xml:id="ex-setup">
    <title>Setting up Differential Equations</title>

    <ol>
      <li>
        Velocity v changes at a rate proportional to v³.
        <solution>
          <p><me>dv/dt = kv^3</me></p>
        </solution>
      </li>

      <li>
        Newton’s Law of Cooling.
        <solution>
          <p><me>dT/dt = k(T - A)</me></p>
        </solution>
      </li>

      <li>
        Slope equals sqrt(xy).
        <solution>
          <p><me>dy/dx = \sqrt{xy}</me></p>
        </solution>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </example>

  <!-- VERIFYING -->
  <example xml:id="ex-verify">
    <title>Verifying Solutions</title>

    <p>
      Verify:
    </p>

    <p><me>y(x) = Ce^{-x^3}, \quad y' + 3x^2 y = 0</me></p>

    <solution>

      <p><strong>Step 1: Differentiate</strong></p>
      <hint>
        <p>Use chain rule on exponential function.</p>
      </hint>

      <p><me>y' = -3x^2 Ce^{-x^3}</me></p>

      <p><strong>Step 2: Substitute into equation</strong></p>
      <hint>
        <p>Replace y and y' into LHS.</p>
      </hint>

      <p>
        <me>y' + 3x^2 y = -3x^2 Ce^{-x^3} + 3x^2 Ce^{-x^3}</me>
      </p>

      <p><strong>Step 3: Simplify</strong></p>
      <p><me>= 0</me></p>

    </solution>
  </example>

  <!-- PRACTICE -->
  <exercise xml:id="ex-practice">
    <title>Practice</title>

    <ol>

      <li>
        Verify y(x)=tan(x^3+C) solves y' = 3x^2(y^2+1).

        <solution>

          <p><strong>Step 1: Differentiate</strong></p>
          <hint>
            <p>Use chain rule with tan(u).</p>
          </hint>

          <p><me>y' = sec^2(x^3+C)\cdot 3x^2</me></p>

          <p><strong>Step 2: Use identity</strong></p>
          <hint>
            <p>sec^2(u) = 1 + tan^2(u)</p>
          </hint>

          <p><me>y' = 3x^2(1 + y^2)</me></p>

        </solution>
      </li>

      <li>
        Is e^x a solution to y'' = -4y?

        <solution>

          <p><strong>Step 1: Compute derivatives</strong></p>
          <p><me>y = e^x, \quad y'' = e^x</me></p>

          <p><strong>Step 2: Substitute</strong></p>
          <p><me>e^x \neq -4e^x</me></p>

          <p><strong>Conclusion:</strong> No</p>

        </solution>
      </li>

      <li>
        Find r such that e^{rt} solves y'' + 5y' + 6y = 0.

        <solution>

          <p><strong>Step 1: Substitute</strong></p>
          <p><me>r^2 e^{rt} + 5r e^{rt} + 6 e^{rt} = 0</me></p>

          <p><strong>Step 2: Factor</strong></p>
          <p><me>r^2 + 5r + 6 = 0</me></p>

          <p><strong>Step 3: Solve</strong></p>
          <p><me>(r+2)(r+3)=0</me></p>

          <p><strong>Final answer:</strong> r = -2, -3</p>

        </solution>
      </li>

    </ol>

  </exercise>

</section>